## 2. **Future Directions Informed by These Papers**

The above works do more than contextualize our research – they also suggest concrete ways to **extend and improve PromptPex and AgentPex**. Here are several future directions inspired by these papers:

*   **Incorporate Multi-Metric Evaluation (Efficiency & Cost):** Kapoor et al. demonstrate that today’s agent evaluations ignore factors like latency or cost. Currently, AgentPex focuses on correctness (rule compliance) and qualitative performance. A future version of AgentPex could integrate **cost metrics** – for example, tracking an agent’s API calls, response time, or token usage during tests. We could then follow Kapoor et al.’s suggestion to *“jointly optimize accuracy and efficiency.”* In practice, AgentPex might output a **cost-vs-compliance analysis**, highlighting if one agent passes all tests with significantly lower resource usage than another. This extension would directly address the call in *AI Agents That Matter* for evaluations that reward simplicity and speed alongside correctness. It would also push our work more toward a full benchmarking suite (not just binary pass/fail), helping users choose agents that are not only reliable but also efficient. [\[arxiv.org\]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.01502)

*   **Automated Test Generation for New Benchmarks:** Yao et al.’s *τ-Bench* introduced the pass^k metric for consistency (running the same scenario k times). We can adopt this idea in AgentPex. A future AgentPex feature could be: when we generate a test scenario, run the agent multiple times and see if outcomes diverge. If an agent succeeds once but fails on slight rephrases or random draws of the same test, AgentPex would flag it as *inconsistent*. This would operationalize the “pass^k” concept and catch flaky behavior. More broadly, we should continually integrate new agent benchmarks as they emerge. For example, Valmeekam et al.’s work on planning with LLMs (*“LLMs Still Can’t Plan”*) provides a suite of classical-planning problems to test reasoning. We could extend PromptPex to generate tests from formal planning domains (via PDDL to text conversion) and check LLM agents’ plan correctness using a solver (much as Valmeekam et al. did manually). In essence, **any new evaluation scenario from research can feed into our test generator**. This keeps our tool up-to-date and ensures that insights like “models fail at planning” are addressed — e.g. by adding a battery of planning-specific test cases to AgentPex. [\[arxiv.org\]](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.12045) [\[openreview.net\]](https://openreview.net/pdf?id=wUU-7XTL5XO)

*   **Tighter Integration of Specifications and Guardrails:** Several class papers highlight the importance of explicit specifications and constraints. For instance, *Cheng et al. (2024)* (from the class reading list on AI assistant ethics) discuss enforcing policies during agent execution. In the future, we could augment PromptPex/AgentPex with a **specification language for developers**. Inspired by SPADE’s declarative approach and Bedrock’s policy prompts, a developer might write something like: *“The agent **must not** reveal user private info. The agent **should** always cite a source for factual answers.”* PromptPex could then auto-generate test cases to stress these requirements (trying to induce the agent to violate them) and AgentPex could monitor live agent conversations for such policy breaks. Essentially, we evolve PromptPex from a testing tool into a combined **testing + guardrailing** framework. By doing so, we embrace the trend in papers like *“Chilling Effects of Oversight”* (Cihon, 2025) that propose runtime oversight: our tool would not just find issues post hoc but actively enforce rules (perhaps by pausing an agent or injecting a correction if a violation is detected). This is a challenging direction (it blurs into runtime monitoring), but it directly follows the trajectory set by related work on responsible AI agents. [\[arxiv.org\]](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.05070)

*   **Enhance Agent Memory and Context Management:** Park et al.’s *Generative Agents* show the power of long-term memory for believable behavior. They also note that components like memory retrieval and reflection critically affect performance (their ablation studies confirm that memory+reflection improved coherence). For AgentPex, this suggests two things: (1) we could make our tests more sophisticated by including **multi-session scenarios** – e.g., test an agent on a task, then later test if it “remembers” facts from the earlier task. This would catch failures of memory. (2) PromptPex/AgentPex could be extended to test an agent’s *internal memory mechanisms*. For example, if an agent uses a vector database to store notes, we might simulate faults (like a note missing) and see if the agent notices inconsistencies. This is speculative, but essentially future PromptPex might generate not only inputs, but also alter the agent’s retrieved context to test robustness against memory errors. By exploring these angles, we align with the cognitive architecture perspective: ensuring an agent’s memory module doesn’t cause rule violations. This direction is informed by CoALA and Generative Agents – they give us a blueprint of agent internals, and we can devise tests targeting each internal part (memory, planner, etc.). [\[arxiv.org\]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.03442)

*   **Cross-Agent and Social Behavior Testing:** A striking result in *Generative Agents* was that complex social phenomena emerged spontaneously. This opens an entirely new frontier for testing: **multi-agent interaction scenarios**. Future AgentPex versions could deploy multiple agent instances in a shared test and observe outcomes. For example, we could test, “Do the agents reach a consensus or do they contradict each other?” or “Does information propagate correctly through the agent society?” (Park et al. showed invitations spreading through a town network). To do this, we’d integrate something like Park’s sandbox as a test environment and use AgentPex to log each agent’s actions against expected social norms. This is ambitious and was outside the scope of our initial work, but it’s a natural progression as agent research moves toward communities of agents. We might collaborate with simulation frameworks to generate events (e.g., one agent lies to see if others detect it). Such multi-agent tests would ensure that AgentPex remains relevant as single-agent systems evolve into **agent ecosystems**. [\[arxiv.org\]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.03442)

*   **Human-in-the-Loop and Adaptive Testing:** Several class discussions emphasized that purely automated evaluation might miss nuances that human eval would catch (for example, subjective correctness or user preference). A future direction is to integrate **human feedback into PromptPex’s loop**. For instance, PromptPex could generate a batch of outputs and ask a human oracle (or use a learned model like OpenAI’s Evals) to label which outputs are acceptable. This labeled data could then guide PromptPex to generate more targeted tests. Essentially, PromptPex could perform a form of *adaptive fuzzing*: if a certain edge case is flagged by humans as problematic, the system generates many variations of that case to probe the model’s behavior limits. This idea aligns with the “Lessons from the Trenches” paper’s advice on reproducible evals (Biderman et al., 2023) which stresses using diverse evaluation methods. By incorporating human judgments, we ensure our test generation doesn’t become blind to issues of quality that are hard to formalize. In turn, this could improve AgentPex’s usefulness for teams concerned with things like answer helpfulness or tone, which are not fully captured by hard rules.

*   **Continuous Integration for LLM Agents:** Finally, an important future step is turning our once-off testing tools into a **continuous integration (CI) system for AI agents**. Many class readings implicitly call for this: Kapoor et al. want benchmarks that evolve with models; OpenAI’s own eval harness (mentioned in class) suggests constantly re-testing models as they update. We envision PromptPex and AgentPex being integrated into deployment pipelines. Whenever a prompt or agent policy is updated (or a new model is swapped in), the CI system would run the full suite of PromptPex/AgentPex tests (including any new ones from recent research) and report regressions immediately. This would prevent the kind of “specification drift” that AgentPex is designed to catch – e.g., if a prompt update inadvertently relaxes a rule, we’d catch it before it reaches end-users. In essence, our tools would become the AI agent equivalent of unit/regression tests in traditional software engineering. This future direction is less about new research insights and more about engineering, but it’s strongly inspired by the ethos of papers like *PromptFoo*, *Evals*, and *Agents that Matter*, all of which advocate for **rigorous, repeatable evaluation**. By implementing a continuous testing framework, we address the scalability and reproducibility concerns raised in those works (e.g., “lack of standardization in evaluation practices”).
